metadata.name: Color of life #61
metadata.description:
console.log("Hello world")

After many thoughts about life, about our relationship as individuals in a society I always bring myself the same doubt, does life become only what we do? Or can we, humans, be personalities without being defined by our professions?

This piece comes from this reflection, when I say that I work with art made with code they soon think that I am an unemployed bum. This work represents the colors that in round and elongated shapes abstract my relationship between code and art, putting beauty in continuous lines, and many times confusing in a general context.

PS: Press [S] to save a png :)

metadata.name: White Night Vol.1 #67
metadata.description:
I have a long-term photography project called “White Night”, which explores special images of trees through black and white inversion.

I attempt to generate similar images by code, and this is the start of the journey.

Made with p5js.

Controls:
- Press “f” to toggle the frame, there is my signature on the mat inside the frame.
- Press “s” to save the image displayed at that moment as a PNG file.
- Change the canvas size by adding “size” URL parameter, for example: &size=1000 (you may add this and lower the number if your device can’t render properly)

metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #232
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Loomnatic #23
metadata.description:
"Loomnatic" is a lunatic loom who loves to weave. It sometimes generates fabrics you can see in real life. However, most of the time, its outputs would look extraordinary.

How the loom "weaves" a fabric:
- Create a vector field for the warp threads with the improved Perlin noise developed by Ken Perlin.
- Derive a new vector field from the old one for the weft threads by rotating its angles.
- Calculate the curve vertices with an algorithm developed by Bruno Jobard and Wilfrid Lefer that creates evenly-spaced streamlines of arbitrary density.
- Interpolate each set of curve vertices to form a Catmull-Rom spline and then convert it to a thread polygon with varying thread weights.
- Calculate the intersection polygons of all pairs of interweaving threads with math and geometry.
- Use the intersection polygons to create the textile effect during the drawing stage.

Every token can output in 13 different aspect ratios:
1x1, 3x1, 1x3, 3x2, 2x3, 4x3, 3x4, 5x4, 4x5, 16x9, 9x16, 16x10, 10x16

And downloadable in 4 different resolutions:
1. 1000px
2. 2000px
3. 4000px
4. 8000px

Click on the image in live view to unlock all these possibilities.

Created with Vanilla JavaScript.

metadata.name: Hexatronic #54
metadata.description: They are the same but different at the same time, they gather in groups and disperse. They call themselves Hexa while continuing to live in the Hexatronic universe. There is a problem - they don't cast shadows. Maybe you can help them.

metadata.name: CrossWorlds #199
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180°
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

objkt.name: Urban Building: Where Are We Going? #126

metadata.name: Urban Building: Where Are We Going? #126
metadata.description:
This is a building generation made by pure code.

Urbanization at the almost everywhere in the world has stepped into an accelerating phase in last century. Buildings bring magnificent achievements and represent the human power over nature. But, following these tall and crowd buildings one by one, where are we going?

In this work, I generate different types of building with a special viewpoint, which represent different concepts of states we are going to. Hope you enjoy these varieties and coincidences.

Variables:
- 4 modes
- 4 environments
- 3 orbs
- 3 building density
- 3 building structures

Please be patient with drawing process.

issuer.name: Urban Building: Where Are We Going?

metadata.name: Lamelle #153
metadata.description:
Lamelle is an exploration of basic rectangles transformed in harmony in 3d.
The name Lamelle(n) is a dutch word for slats, what the art reminded me off.

Press e to save a 4000x4000 PNG in live mode.

Made with basic HTML and javascript

Lammetje
May 2022
